# Application Layer

Coordinates business logic. No framework or I/O code.

## Structure

| Path | Contents |
|------|----------|
| `ports/inbound/` | Driving port interfaces |
| `ports/outbound/` | Driven port interfaces |
| `use_cases/{context}/` | One use case per intent |
| `dto/` | Request/response crossing boundaries |
| `mappers/` | Domain entity ↔ DTO (no ORM models) |

## Use Case Rules

- Depend on `domain/` and outbound **port abstractions** only.
- Never import `infrastructure/` or `interfaces/`.
- Inject ports via constructor; no `new ConcreteRepository()` inside use cases.
- `execute()` accepts a command/query DTO; returns result DTO or raises domain error.

## Orchestration

`use_cases/orchestration/ProcessPlatePipelineUseCase` sequences pipeline stages — individual stage logic stays in dedicated use cases or domain services.

## DTOs vs Domain

| DTO | Domain |
|-----|--------|
| API/use-case boundaries | Business rules |
| Serializable, flat | Rich behavior |
| In `application/dto/` | In `domain/` |

Convert at use case boundary: `PlateNumber.from_string(dto.plate_text)`.

## Port Segregation

Small, focused ports — not a monolithic `AIServicePort`:

- `PlateDetectionPort`, `OcrPort`, `VehicleRegistryPort`, `SightingRepositoryPort`

## Review Checklist

- [ ] No SQLAlchemy, FastAPI, cv2, paddleocr imports
- [ ] No HTTP or file I/O
- [ ] Each use case file = one class, one responsibility
